## Clark County, Nevada

This is a [county](/County_(United_States)) in [Nevada](/Nevada), a state within the [United States](/United_States). It's in the southernmost part of the state, which is saying something, considering Nevada’s general disposition. It's also the most populous. Apparently, people find this desert appealing. Go figure.

### Overview

Clark County is the [county seat](/County_seat) of [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas). Yes, *that* Las Vegas. The one where people go to forget things. It’s the largest city in the county, and also the largest city in the state. Then there’s [Henderson](/Henderson,_Nevada) and [North Las Vegas](/North_Las_Vegas,_Nevada), which are just… more of it, really. It’s also where you’ll find the infamous [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), a monument to excess and questionable decisions. Not to mention [Nellis Air Force Base](/Nellis_Air_Force_Base), which is probably the only place in the county with any real purpose, and the [Hoover Dam](/Hoover_Dam), a colossal exercise in concrete and misplaced optimism.

The county itself spans 8,061 square miles (20,880 km²). That's roughly the size of [New Jersey](/New_Jersey). But Nevada's got a lot of empty space, so it’s effectively just a backdrop. Despite housing 70% of Nevada's population, making it the [11th-most populous county](/List_of_the_most_populous_counties_in_the_United_States) in the whole country, it only accounts for about 7% of the state's landmass. Most of the people live in [unincorporated](/Unincorporated_towns_in_Nevada) areas, which means the county itself handles things like [municipal services](/Municipal_services). It’s a bit of a mess, frankly. The county government has jurisdiction over the [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), which is… fitting, I suppose. It’s a place where rules seem to bend, or perhaps just cease to exist.

The governing body is the [Clark County Commission](/Clark_County_Commission), a seven-member elected group. They make the rules, and then they appoint a [county manager](/County_executive) to actually *do* things. The [Las Vegas Metropolitan Police Department](/Las_Vegas_Metropolitan_Police_Department) covers most of the law enforcement, a merger of the city and county forces. I’m sure that went smoothly.

This land was originally home to the [Southern Paiute people](/Southern_Paiute_people), among others. Then it became part of Mexico’s [Alta California](/Alta_California), and after the [Mexican-American War](/Mexican%E2%80%93American_War), it fell under the United States. It was shuffled around as part of the [New Mexico Territory](/New_Mexico_Territory) and later the [Arizona Territory](/Arizona_Territory) before becoming part of Nevada as [Lincoln County](/Lincoln_County,_Nevada). Clark County itself was carved out of Lincoln County in 1909. A rather arbitrary division, if you ask me.

### History

[Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas), the big, bright beacon of… whatever it is, has been the [county seat](/County_seat) since the county's inception. The [Nevada Legislature](/Nevada_Legislature) decided to split off a chunk of [Lincoln County](/Lincoln_County,_Nevada) on February 5, 1909, and by July 1, 1909, Clark County was officially a thing. The [Las Vegas Valley](/Las_Vegas_Valley_(landform)), a vast, arid basin, is home to Las Vegas and its surrounding sprawl, including [North Las Vegas](/North_Las_Vegas), [Henderson](/Henderson,_Nevada), and the unceremoniously named [Paradise](/Paradise,_Nevada).

Native Americans, specifically the Paiutes, were here for millennia, as early as AD 700. Before that, it was part of the Mexican Territory of [Alta California](/Alta_California). Then came the American [beaver](/Beaver) trappers, who apparently found something worth traipsing through the desert for. This eventually led to [Antonio Armijo](/Antonio_Armijo), a merchant from New Mexico, establishing a trade route in 1829, the [Armijo Route](/Old_Spanish_Trail_(trade_route)), later known as the [Old Spanish Trail](/Old_Spanish_Trail_(trade_route)). It passed through the area, following the [Virgin](/Virgin_River) and [Colorado Rivers](/Colorado_River). Eventually, merchants, trappers, and assorted others modified it, seeking a more direct path. In Clark County, this meant a northward route away from the Colorado, relying on a string of creeks and springs, like the ones at [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas). [John C. Frémont](/John_C._Fr%C3%A9mont) added his own detour, [Frémont's Cutoff](/Old_Spanish_Trail_(trade_route)), on his way back to Utah in 1844.

After the [Mexican–American War](/Mexican%E2%80%93American_War), this land became part of the United States, specifically the northwestern edge of the [New Mexico Territory](/New_Mexico_Territory). In 1847, returning [Mormon Battalion](/Mormon_Battalion) members, led by [Jefferson Hunt](/Jefferson_Hunt), blazed a wagon trail that became the [Mormon Road](/Mormon_Road). By 1849, this was known as the "Southern Route," a winter alternative for the [California Trail](/California_Trail) connecting Salt Lake City to Los Angeles, especially during the [California Gold Rush](/California_Gold_Rush). By the mid-1850s, this route, by then called the Salt Lake Road in California and the California Road in [Utah Territory](/Utah_Territory), was a significant wagon trade route. The Mormons even established a [Mormon Fort](/Old_Las_Vegas_Mormon_Fort_State_Historic_Park) in [Las Vegas](/Las_Vegas) in the mid-1850s. They also set up colonies along the Virgin and [Muddy Rivers](/Muddy_River_(Nevada)).

When the [Arizona Territory](/Arizona_Territory) was formed in 1863, all of what is now Clark County was part of [Mohave County](/Mohave_County,_Arizona). It then became part of [Pah-Ute County, Arizona Territory](/Pah-Ute_County,_Arizona_Territory) in 1865. The part north and west of the Colorado River was ceded to Nevada in 1866, though Arizona territory held out until 1871. Eventually, this territory became part of Lincoln County, and the westernmost section was absorbed by [Nye County](/Nye_County,_Nevada).

The county was named after [William A. Clark](/William_A._Clark), a copper magnate from [Montana](/Montana) and a [U.S. Senator](/United_States_Senate). He was instrumental in building the [San Pedro, Los Angeles and Salt Lake Railroad](/Los_Angeles_and_Salt_Lake_Railroad), which, predictably, helped develop the region. Now, Clark County is a major tourist trap, boasting around 150,000 hotel rooms. The [Las Vegas Strip](/Las_Vegas_Strip), where all the famous casinos reside, isn't actually within the City of Las Vegas limits. It’s in unincorporated Paradise, but still within the [Las Vegas Valley](/Las_Vegas_Valley). It’s all rather… tangled.

Clark County is synonymous with the [Las Vegas MSA](/Las_Vegas_Metropolitan_Statistical_Area), a designation used for statistical purposes. The region has been grappling with increasing [droughts](/Drought) due to [climate change](/Climate_change), putting a strain on [water security](/Water_security). Just another charming facet of this desert paradise.

### Geography

The [Colorado River](/Colorado_River) forms the southeastern border, with the [Hoover Dam](/Hoover_Dam) creating [Lake Mead](/Lake_Mead) along much of it. The absolute lowest point in all of Nevada is right here, on the Colorado River, just south of [Laughlin](/Laughlin,_Nevada), where it flows into [California](/California) and [Arizona](/Arizona). The greater Las Vegas area is a tectonic valley, surrounded by mountains. [Mount Charleston](/Mount_Charleston) to the northwest is the highest point, reaching 11,918 feet (3,633 m). Beyond the forests on Mount Charleston, it's mostly desert. Thorny creosote bushes are the dominant vegetation, and the mountains are bare rock. The terrain generally slopes towards the south and east. The county covers 8,061 square miles (20,880 km²), with 7,891 square miles (20,440 km²) of land and 170 square miles (440 km²) of water. A significant portion, 2.1%, is water.

